Interview Questions
1) What are the naming rules for Java packages?
-->Built-in packages are predefined packages provided by Java that contain commonly used classes and interfaces.

    👉 They are part of the Java Standard Library and help developers avoid writing code from scratch.
    
    Examples:
    java.lang → core classes (String, Math, System)
    java.util → utilities (ArrayList, Scanner, HashMap)
    java.io → input/output classes (File, BufferedReader)
    java.sql → database connectivity
    java.net → networking



2) Can a package name start with a number or special character?
-->
| Feature        | `java.lang`                  | `java.util`                       |
| -------------- | ---------------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Purpose        | Core language classes        | Utility classes                   |
| Import         | Automatically imported       | Must be imported manually         |
| Common Classes | String, System, Math, Object | ArrayList, Scanner, HashMap, Date |
| Usage          | Basic operations             | Data structures & utilities       |

👉 Example:
// java.lang (no import needed)
String name = "Karthikeya";

// java.util (import required)
import java.util.ArrayList;
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();



3) Why is lowercase recommended for package names?
-->The java.lang package is automatically imported by default
    👉 That’s why you can directly use:
    
    String
    System
    Math
    Object
    without writing an import statement.



4) Explain the use of reverse domain name convention in package naming.
-->The reverse domain name convention is used to make package names unique globally.

👉 Format:

    com.company.project
    
    👉 It is based on your website domain:
    
    Website: example.com
    Package: com.example
    
    Why it is used:
    
    Avoids naming conflicts between different organizations
    Provides uniqueness across projects
    Makes packages more organized and meaningful
    
    👉 Example:
    
    com.google.util
    org.apache.commons
    com.karthikeya.app



    
5) Can two packages have the same name in Java? What happens?
-->✅ Yes, they can have the same name, but only if they are in different classpaths or locations.
    
    👉 What happens:
    
    JVM identifies classes using fully qualified names
    If two classes have the same package + class name → conflict occurs
    
    👉 Example conflict:
    com.app.Test   // Package 1
    com.app.Test   // Package 2
    
    ❗ This leads to:
    Ambiguity error during compilation
    JVM may load the wrong class depending on classpath order
    👉 Solution:
    Use unique package names (reverse domain convention)
    Avoid duplicate fully qualified names



    
6) What are the restrictions on special characters in package names?
-->Package names must follow Java identifier rules.  
    ❌ Not allowed:
    
    Special characters like @, #, %, &, *
    Spaces
    Starting with a number
    
    ✅ Allowed:
    Lowercase letters (a–z)
    Digits (but not at the start)
    Underscore _ (rarely used)
    
    👉 Examples:
    
    ✔ Valid:
    com.example.project1
    com.karthikeya_app
    
    ❌ Invalid:
    com.example@project   // special character
    com.my project        // space
    123package.name       // starts with number
